Predictive Modeling

Broadly, can organize goals as

  • Unsupervised learning - goal is to learn about patterns and relationships in the data

    • No output to shoot for

  • Supervised learning - a variable or variables in the data set represent an 'output' of interest

    • May wish to make inference on the model
    • Often just want to predict response(s)

Supervised Learning

Commonly used supervised methods are

  • Regression models
    • Least squares
    • Penalized regression
    • Locally weighted/splines
    • Generalized linear models
  • Tree based methods
    • Regression/classification trees
    • Random forests, boosting, bagging

… and many more, tons of methods!

Predictive Modeling

Where to start?

  • Not going to focus on inference (applied statistics sequence covers that well!)

  • Start with basic linear regression models

  • Expand to different types of responses in the exponential family

  • Explore tree methods

  • Look at ensemble type methods to improve prediction

Lastly, we'll look at some unsupervised methods like clustering and PCA

Regression/Classification Trees

Tree based method:

  • Split up predictor space into regions, different predictions for each region

Regression/Classification Trees

Tree based method:

  • Split up predictor space into regions, different predictions for each region

  • Classification tree if goal is to classify (predict) group membership
    • For a given region, usually use most prevalent class as prediction

Regression/Classification Trees

Tree based method:

  • Split up predictor space into regions, different predictions for each region

  • Classification tree if goal is to classify (predict) group membership
    • For a given region, usually use most prevalent class as prediction
  • Regression tree if goal is to predict a continuous response
    • For a given region, usually use mean of observations as prediction

library(tree) #rpart is also often used
fitTree <- tree(dist ~ speed, data = cars) #default splitting is deviance
plot(fitTree)
text(fitTree)

Tree vs SLR Comparison

Tree vs Polynomial Regression Comparison

Regression/Classification Trees

  • Can still predict with predict()
predict(fitTree, newdata = data.frame(speed = c(10, 20)))
## [1] 23.22222 55.71429

  • Extension to more than one predictor is exactly the same idea

  • Instead of fitting a plane or saddle, fit a series of flat planes (mean for a given region)

Tree Visual

Trees automatically account for interactions

#set up prediction explanatory variables
grid.lines = 60
x.pred <- seq(min(subVoting$pop.change), max(subVoting$pop.change), length.out = grid.lines)
y.pred <- seq(min(subVoting$college), max(subVoting$college), length.out = grid.lines)
xy <- expand.grid(pop.change = x.pred, college = y.pred)
#predictions
z.tree.pred <- matrix(predict(treeFit, newdata = xy), 
                                 nrow = grid.lines, ncol = grid.lines)
# scatter plot with regression plane (rgl package)
plot3d(x = subVoting$pop.change, y = subVoting$college, z = subVoting$income,
                    cex = 0.8, theta = 20, phi = 20, ticktype = "detailed",
                    xlab = "Pop Change", ylab = "Per College", zlab = 
"Income")
#add surfaces
surface3d(x = x.pred, y = y.pred, z = z.tree.pred, color = "blue")

Regression/Classification Trees

Tree based method:

  • Split up predictor space into regions, different predictions for each region

  • Classification tree if goal is to classify (predict) group membership
    • For a given region, usually use most prevalent class as prediction
  • Regression tree if goal is to predict a continuous response
    • For a given region, usually use mean of observations as prediction

Classification Tree

  • Break up region by yards and give prediction

  • Prediction = most common outcome in class

FGTreeFit <- tree(outcome ~ yards, data = FGData, split = "deviance")
FGTreeFit
## node), split, n, deviance, yval, (yprob)
##       * denotes terminal node
## 
## 1) root 17104 16510 good ( 0.81244 0.18756 )  
##   2) yards < 36.5 8365  4414 good ( 0.92600 0.07400 )  
##     4) yards < 27.5 3938  1053 good ( 0.97029 0.02971 ) *
##     5) yards > 27.5 4427  3130 good ( 0.88660 0.11340 ) *
##   3) yards > 36.5 8739 10620 good ( 0.70374 0.29626 )  
##     6) yards < 47.5 5873  6467 good ( 0.76043 0.23957 ) *
##     7) yards > 47.5 2866  3885 good ( 0.58758 0.41242 ) *

Misclassification rate important measure of how good the tree is!

This is on the training set though…

summary(FGTreeFit)
## 
## Classification tree:
## tree(formula = outcome ~ yards, data = FGData, split = "deviance")
## Number of terminal nodes:  4 
## Residual mean deviance:  0.85 = 14540 / 17100 
## Misclassification error rate: 0.1876 = 3208 / 17104

Classification Tree

Classify all as good! (all classes have at least 50% made)

plot(FGTreeFit)
text(FGTreeFit)

Visual of Proportion in Each Class

Classification Tree

Prediction with predict()

  • Can get probability predictions. Not great with this method but a reasonable start
predict(FGTreeFit, newdata = data.frame(yards = c(25, 40, 50)))
##        good    no good
## 1 0.9702895 0.02971051
## 2 0.7604291 0.23957092
## 3 0.5875785 0.41242149
  • Just predict the class
predict(FGTreeFit, type = "class", newdata = data.frame(yards = c(25, 40, 50, 60)))
## [1] good good good good
## Levels: good no good
